  9  /-!
 10  # equivs in the algebraic hierarchy
 11  
 12  In the first part there are theorems of the following
 13  form: if `α` has a group structure and `α ≃ β` then `β` has a group structure, and
 14  similarly for monoids, semigroups, rings, integral domains, fields and so on.
 15  
 16  In the second part there are extensions of `equiv` called `add_equiv`,
 17  `mul_equiv`, and `ring_equiv`, which are datatypes representing
 18  isomorphisms of add_monoids/add_groups, monoids/groups and rings. We
 19  also introduce the corresponding groups of automorphisms `add_aut`,
 20  `mul_aut`, and `ring_aut`.
 21  
 22  ## Notations
 23  
 24  The extended equivs all have coercions to functions, and the coercions are the canonical
 25  notation when treating the isomorphisms as maps.
 26  
 27  ## Implementation notes
 28  
 29  The fields for `mul_equiv`, `add_equiv`, and `ring_equiv` now avoid
 30  the unbundled `is_mul_hom` and `is_add_hom`, as these are deprecated.
 31  
 32  Definition of multiplication in the groups of automorphisms agrees
 33  with function composition, multiplication in `equiv.perm`, and
 34  multiplication in `category_theory.End`, not with
 35  `category_theory.comp`.
 36  
 37  ## Tags
 38  
 39  equiv, mul_equiv, add_equiv, ring_equiv, mul_aut, add_aut, ring_aut
 40  -/
